Choose the correct match from the options below:

A small point mass object is thrown in a vertical downward direction with an initial velocity of $50\text{ m/s}$ from the top of a building. It covers $95\text{ m}$ of distance during its last second before impact. If the coefficient of restitution is $e = 0.6$, the fraction of the building's height covered during the first rebound is ________. ($g = 10 \text{ m/s}^2$)

A boat starts moving across a river with a velocity of $9\text{ km/h}$ relative to the water. The river is flowing at a rate of $6\text{ km/h}$. The magnitude of the resultant velocity of the boat as observed from the river bank is ________ $\text{km/h}$.

A particle of mass $m$ is released from a height $S = 80\text{ m}$ above the surface of the earth. At a certain height $x$, its kinetic energy is three times its potential energy. The speed of the particle at this instant is ________ $\text{ms}^{-1}$. (Take $g = 10\text{ ms}^{-2}$)

Consider a rubber ball freely falling from a height $h = 4.9$ m onto a horizontal elastic plate. Assume that the duration of collision is negligible and the collision with the plate is totally elastic. Then the velocity as a function of time and the height as a function of time will be:

A satellite of mass $m = 500\text{ kg}$ is to be projected from the earth's surface to infinity. Taking the radius of the earth as $R_E = 6.4 \times 10^6\text{ m}$ and the acceleration due to gravity as $g = 10\text{ ms}^{-2}$, the required kinetic energy is ________ $\times 10^{10}\text{ J}$.

Two copper vessels $A$ and $B$ have the same base area but of different shapes. $A$ takes twice the volume of water as that $B$ requires to fill upto a particular common height. Then the correct statement among the following is:
questions.option_b: Pressure on the base area of vessels $A$ and $B$ is same.
questions.option_c: Pressure on the base area of vessels $A$ and $B$ is not same.
questions.option_d: Both vessels $A$ and $B$ weigh the same.

Given below are two statements:

$\pmb{\text{Statement I :}}$ The law of radioactive decay states that the number of nuclei undergoing the decay per unit time is inversely proportional to the total number of nuclei in the sample.

$\pmb{\text{Statement II :}}$ The half-life of a radionuclide is the sum of the lifetime of all nuclei, divided by the initial concentration of the nuclei at time $t = 0$.

In the light of the above statements, choose the most appropriate answer from the options given below:
questions.option_a: Statement I is incorrect but statement II is correct
questions.option_b: Both statement I and statement II are correct
questions.option_c: Both statement I and statement II are incorrect
questions.option_d: Statement I is correct but statement II is incorrect

u \end{aligned}$$
